WEBVTT

00:02.208 --> 00:03.417
-NARRATOR: Tonight...
-Let's get some gold, baby!

00:03.542 --> 00:05.333
-Yes!
-...on <i>Beyond Oak Island...</i>

00:05.458 --> 00:08.583
The American Gold Rush actually
started in North Carolina.

00:08.708 --> 00:11.917
-Wow.
-Oh, my gosh.

00:12.042 --> 00:15.083
Tim and Ross Fisher found
a massive gold dredge

00:15.208 --> 00:17.125
-on their property.
-What's your estimate?

00:17.208 --> 00:19.542
There's two billion dollars'
worth of gold.

00:19.667 --> 00:21.458
-It's like Christmas, guys.
-Let's open some presents.

00:22.708 --> 00:24.167
-TIM: See anything, Ross?
-MATTY: You think that's gold?

00:24.292 --> 00:25.833
-Yeah, it's gold.
-No way!

00:25.958 --> 00:27.708
-I can't believe it.
-Ahh!

00:27.875 --> 00:28.750
(laughing)

00:28.875 --> 00:30.333
-(whoops)
-Yes!

00:32.417 --> 00:34.083
All the while
we were growing up,

00:34.208 --> 00:37.458
my brother and I were fascinated
with finding treasure.

00:38.708 --> 00:39.542
RICK:
Pirate treasure,

00:39.667 --> 00:41.000
cursed treasure.

00:41.125 --> 00:43.083
Civil War gold.

00:43.208 --> 00:45.958
-(laughter)
-Since then,
our work on Oak Island

00:46.042 --> 00:48.167
has shown us
there's a world of mysteries...

00:48.250 --> 00:51.167
-Whoa.
-...waiting to be explored.

00:51.250 --> 00:54.042
RICK:
So, we like to reach out
to other treasure hunters.

00:54.167 --> 00:56.250
X marks the spot, right there.
Brilliant.

00:56.375 --> 00:58.500
-MARTY: We want to hear
their stories...
-That's right.

00:58.625 --> 01:01.125
-...and share our insights.
-"Ill-gotten gains."

01:01.208 --> 01:02.500
-RICK: And who knows...
-GARY: I got it.

01:02.583 --> 01:04.333
...maybe we can help them
with their search.

01:04.417 --> 01:06.000
MARTY:
Not only in America.

01:06.125 --> 01:07.833
Wow. That is gold.

01:07.917 --> 01:09.708
-RICK: But all over the world.
-Yeah!

01:09.875 --> 01:11.500
MARTY:
<i>Beyond Oak Island.</i>

01:19.208 --> 01:20.583
MATTY: You know,
the reason I called you

01:20.708 --> 01:23.125
in the war room today
is because I wonder how you guys

01:23.250 --> 01:24.958
-are gonna react to this word.
-All right.

01:25.083 --> 01:26.500
Gold.

01:26.625 --> 01:29.125
Oh, baby.
(chuckles)

01:29.208 --> 01:31.750
Who reacts any different
to that word?

01:31.875 --> 01:33.292
Say the word "treasure,"

01:33.417 --> 01:35.042
what's the first word
that comes to your mind?

01:35.208 --> 01:36.000
-Gold.
-Gold.

01:36.167 --> 01:37.167
There you go.

01:37.250 --> 01:39.083
I'm gonna cut to the chase.

01:39.208 --> 01:41.833
Because I've always thought
of the '49er,

01:41.958 --> 01:45.167
San Francisco, the Gold Rush,
you know, an old prospector

01:45.333 --> 01:47.000
with a pickaxe
and a pan, right?

01:47.083 --> 01:49.000
-Mm-hmm.
-Well, I've come to learn

01:49.083 --> 01:51.042
recently that
that's not even close

01:51.167 --> 01:52.667
to the whole story in America,

01:52.792 --> 01:54.833
and that the Gold Rush

01:54.958 --> 01:58.167
actually started
in North Carolina.

01:58.292 --> 02:00.250
In fact, not only did it start
in North Carolina,

02:00.375 --> 02:04.167
every bit of gold that went to
the U.S. Treasury domestically

02:04.333 --> 02:09.833
from 1804 to 1828
was found in North Carolina.

02:09.917 --> 02:11.625
-Wow.
-I didn't know that.

02:13.167 --> 02:15.167
NARRATOR: The first
great era of gold mining

02:15.250 --> 02:17.333
in the United States began

02:17.458 --> 02:20.125
under the most unlikely
of circumstances--

02:20.208 --> 02:22.833
when a young boy
made a chance discovery

02:22.958 --> 02:26.500
near Charlotte,
North Carolina, in 1799.

02:26.583 --> 02:28.708
BALDWIN:
A 12-year-old boy
named Conrad Reed

02:28.875 --> 02:32.292
went fishing one afternoon
on his family farm,

02:32.375 --> 02:36.958
and he stumbled across
a 17-pound nugget.

02:37.042 --> 02:38.542
At the time,
he didn't know what he had.

02:38.708 --> 02:42.250
He brought it home, showed it
to his father, John Reed.

02:42.375 --> 02:44.167
And John obviously didn't know
what he had, either,

02:44.333 --> 02:47.500
because he used that nugget
for a doorstop.

02:47.625 --> 02:51.792
And for about five years,
that nugget stayed in his home,

02:51.917 --> 02:54.667
behind a door, until a jeweler

02:54.750 --> 02:58.833
saw what he had and
offered him some money for it.

02:58.917 --> 03:01.167
He ended up paying $3.50,

03:01.333 --> 03:05.375
which was valued
about $66 in today's money,

03:05.500 --> 03:10.542
for that 17-pound,
22-karat nugget.

03:11.542 --> 03:13.333
NARRATOR:
Although John Reed was not paid

03:13.458 --> 03:17.458
what the 17-pound golden
nugget was worth in 1799,

03:17.542 --> 03:21.250
which was approximately $5,000,

03:21.375 --> 03:23.917
he soon found
another one on his property

03:24.042 --> 03:27.208
weighing an astonishing
28 pounds.

03:27.333 --> 03:30.042
The discovery spread
in the local newspapers,

03:30.167 --> 03:32.167
leading to many farmers
in the area

03:32.292 --> 03:34.375
becoming part-time gold miners

03:34.542 --> 03:37.167
and searching the rivers
and streams on their land

03:37.292 --> 03:39.000
throughout the state.

03:39.125 --> 03:42.667
By 1804, so much gold
was being recovered

03:42.833 --> 03:45.333
that a wave of highly skilled
Cornish miners from England

03:45.458 --> 03:47.583
emigrated to the United States,

03:47.708 --> 03:50.333
sparking the nation's
first gold rush.

03:50.500 --> 03:52.125
BALDWIN: At the peak
of the gold mining

03:52.208 --> 03:54.708
in North Carolina,
there were 600 mines

03:54.833 --> 03:56.667
all the way through
seven or eight counties.

03:56.750 --> 03:59.667
In fact, there was
so much gold being produced

03:59.750 --> 04:03.083
that a branch of the government
built a mint in Charlotte

04:03.208 --> 04:04.875
just for those gold coins.

04:05.000 --> 04:07.083
Stories are fanciful

04:07.208 --> 04:09.500
of just reaching your hand
into a riverbed

04:09.625 --> 04:12.667
and pulling up
huge nuggets of gold.

04:12.792 --> 04:15.958
To a growing nation,
those types of stories

04:16.083 --> 04:17.833
are irresistible.

04:17.917 --> 04:19.458
Finding gold wasn't luck.

04:19.542 --> 04:22.750
It was a combination
of art and science.

04:22.875 --> 04:26.333
NARRATOR: Gold mining
in both North and South Carolina

04:26.417 --> 04:28.500
would produce millions
of dollars in gold

04:28.625 --> 04:30.833
over the next half century,

04:30.958 --> 04:34.333
until the California Gold Rush
began in 1848,

04:34.417 --> 04:36.708
which spurred
many skilled miners

04:36.833 --> 04:38.667
to pick up and head west

04:38.833 --> 04:41.833
in search of new
and greater fortunes.

04:42.000 --> 04:44.000
BALDWIN:
The North Carolina mines

04:44.083 --> 04:46.542
operated for around 100 years.

04:46.708 --> 04:48.667
And in my opinion,
there's still

04:48.750 --> 04:50.375
millions of dollars'
worth of gold

04:50.500 --> 04:51.792
just waiting to be discovered.

04:53.750 --> 04:55.375
There was a gold rush
before the Gold Rush

04:55.542 --> 04:58.167
in North Carolina,
someplace I've been many times,

04:58.250 --> 04:59.458
but never knew that history.

04:59.542 --> 05:01.542
And I stumbled across
this article

05:01.667 --> 05:04.000
about a family,
Tim and Ross Fisher.

05:04.125 --> 05:05.125
-Okay.
-And these guys...

05:05.250 --> 05:06.583
-Father-son?
-Father-son.

05:06.708 --> 05:10.500
They found a giant,
massive gold dredge

05:10.583 --> 05:13.500
on their property,
and they are uncovering it

05:13.667 --> 05:17.208
and basically trying to make it
almost like a living museum,

05:17.333 --> 05:19.167
but also, they're finding
gold on that property.

05:19.333 --> 05:22.083
-Mm-hmm.
-MATTY: So,
they are finding gold

05:22.208 --> 05:24.000
in the dredge itself.

05:24.125 --> 05:25.833
-Hm.
-Remnants of the gold.

05:25.917 --> 05:28.500
And they are more than eager
to talk to us,

05:28.625 --> 05:29.667
if you guys want to try
and find some gold.

05:29.833 --> 05:31.083
MARTY:
Well, it sounds interesting.

05:31.208 --> 05:32.500
-Sounds real interesting.
-Right?

05:32.625 --> 05:33.250
RICK: Different sort
of approach, isn't it?

05:33.375 --> 05:34.417
Well, let's talk to him.

05:34.542 --> 05:35.875
Yeah?
Let's hunt some gold!

05:36.042 --> 05:36.833
-Yeah.
-North Carolina style.

05:36.958 --> 05:38.417
North Carolina gold.

05:38.542 --> 05:40.250
Let's go to the South,
gentlemen.

05:40.375 --> 05:41.542
And there they are.

05:41.667 --> 05:43.250
(overlapping greetings)

05:43.375 --> 05:45.583
-What's up, guys?
-Hey, how's it going?

05:45.708 --> 05:48.042
Well, it's Matty Blake here,

05:48.208 --> 05:50.458
and I have Rick
and Marty Lagina with me.

05:50.542 --> 05:53.458
I know we spoke via email,
but could you fill us in

05:53.542 --> 05:55.875
on what exactly you found
on your property,

05:56.000 --> 05:57.208
and what's happening now?

05:57.375 --> 06:01.292
Sure, I would say
probably seven years ago

06:01.417 --> 06:03.042
we purchased some land.

06:03.167 --> 06:06.667
It was gold mine land
in Nash County, North Carolina.

06:06.750 --> 06:08.708
We paid a bit of money
for this land.

06:08.875 --> 06:11.417
We knew it was gold mine land,
but we got picked on--

06:11.542 --> 06:13.708
Yeah, part of that's a valley,
and it's just, you know...

06:13.875 --> 06:16.167
-Swampy land.
-It's not really the best place

06:16.250 --> 06:18.375
to buy land.
It's like, well, you know...

06:18.542 --> 06:19.833
-We're gonna do it anyways.
-We're gonna buy it anyway.

06:19.958 --> 06:22.125
So, we bought it,
and the funny thing is,

06:22.250 --> 06:24.625
two years later,
then we discovered

06:24.708 --> 06:26.875
this big dredge and all that,
and we had no idea.

06:27.000 --> 06:28.667
And the same people
that were talking junk,

06:28.750 --> 06:30.250
they wanted to come down
and get a tour.

06:30.375 --> 06:31.625
-Yeah.
-Yes.

06:31.750 --> 06:34.333
-That's the way it works.
-MATTY: Yeah.

06:34.458 --> 06:35.792
My name's Tim Fisher,

06:35.875 --> 06:37.833
and I'm from Nashville,
North Carolina.

06:37.958 --> 06:39.167
And Ross Fisher, my son.

06:39.292 --> 06:41.125
Me and my dad
are gold prospectors,

06:41.208 --> 06:42.708
treasure hunters.

06:42.875 --> 06:45.125
The Indiana Jones
of North Carolina, if you will.

06:45.250 --> 06:48.500
TIM:
We discovered a dredge in 2019.

06:48.667 --> 06:50.833
It was like
uncovering a painting.

06:50.958 --> 06:53.833
It was like...
It just was staggering.

06:53.917 --> 06:56.250
NARRATOR: The dredge,
which was constructed

06:56.375 --> 06:59.750
in the early 1900s,
is actually a ship

06:59.875 --> 07:02.250
that was designed
to float in shallow water

07:02.375 --> 07:05.167
while scooping soil
into compartments.

07:05.292 --> 07:07.875
These collected materials
were then sifted

07:08.000 --> 07:09.542
through an onboard sluice

07:09.667 --> 07:12.458
to separate fine gold
from the sediment.

07:12.583 --> 07:17.542
Abandoned around 1912,
over time the vessel sank

07:17.667 --> 07:19.750
into the mud,
where it was preserved

07:19.875 --> 07:23.125
until the Fishers
discovered it in 2019.

07:24.375 --> 07:26.417
TIM:
This dredge had been lost
for 100 years.

07:26.542 --> 07:27.625
But we do know
that there's still

07:27.708 --> 07:29.000
quite a lot of gold in it.

07:29.167 --> 07:31.708
We are finding gold in there.

07:31.875 --> 07:34.167
You know, it's small gold,
but it's a lot of it.

07:34.333 --> 07:35.833
It's just taking us more time.

07:35.958 --> 07:38.958
Our ultimate plan
for this whole crazy thing

07:39.042 --> 07:43.000
that we're doing, is we want
to dig this dredge up.

07:43.167 --> 07:45.167
We would like to turn it
into more like a museum.

07:45.333 --> 07:47.500
We're preserving a piece
of the past for people to see,

07:47.667 --> 07:49.792
so telling the story.

07:49.875 --> 07:52.542
-That's the true treasure to us.
-Yeah, true.

07:52.667 --> 07:55.500
Where are you guys right now,

07:55.625 --> 07:58.250
in terms of your efforts
to uncover this dredge?

07:58.375 --> 07:59.667
How much have you done?

07:59.750 --> 08:02.333
Well, we've got half
of the dredge uncovered.

08:02.500 --> 08:03.917
-On top.
-To where you can see

08:04.042 --> 08:05.667
the footprint real clear.

08:05.750 --> 08:07.042
-Okay.
-The timbers.

08:07.208 --> 08:08.333
So, we're just getting started.

08:08.458 --> 08:10.750
And the crazy thing
about all this

08:10.875 --> 08:15.333
is this dredge is buried
three feet underground.

08:15.458 --> 08:18.333
It's 94 feet long,
it's 32 feet wide.

08:18.458 --> 08:19.500
-Geez.
-That's big.

08:19.667 --> 08:22.375
-Wow.
-We've built this crane

08:22.542 --> 08:25.542
to get to the lower sections
of the dredge

08:25.708 --> 08:27.875
to get the material out
where we can find

08:28.000 --> 08:32.333
a lot of the bigger gold,
more gold, and possibly...

08:32.500 --> 08:34.083
-Artifacts, yeah.
-...artifacts.

08:34.208 --> 08:36.917
There's obviously--
and no pun intended--

08:37.042 --> 08:38.875
you know,
it's rich history here.

08:39.042 --> 08:41.875
So, you must have
thought about, you know,

08:42.042 --> 08:44.833
how much-- I'll call them
gold reserves--

08:44.958 --> 08:47.500
still are in the area.
What's your estimate?

08:47.583 --> 08:51.583
Just in the area, there's
two billion dollars' worth

08:51.708 --> 08:52.750
of gold sitting right now.

08:52.875 --> 08:54.333
-Still in there.
-Billion.

08:54.458 --> 08:55.833
Not million, billion.

08:55.958 --> 08:57.500
-(chuckling)
-He wants to be clear on that.

08:57.667 --> 08:59.875
And that's not including
probably what's in

09:00.000 --> 09:01.708
those tailing piles,
those dredge piles.

09:01.833 --> 09:04.875
There's acres of dredge piles
that's never been touched,

09:05.042 --> 09:06.917
ten feet deep,
that there's gotta be

09:07.042 --> 09:08.500
some good gold in there.

09:09.708 --> 09:11.833
NARRATOR: As the dredge
traversed the land,

09:11.958 --> 09:15.250
digging as deep
as 30 feet into the ground,

09:15.375 --> 09:18.000
finer materials
were sifted for gold.

09:18.083 --> 09:21.250
However, much of the sediment
and large rocks

09:21.375 --> 09:23.458
were immediately ejected
from the vessel,

09:23.583 --> 09:25.417
forming large piles.

09:25.542 --> 09:27.667
They wouldn't catch
all the big gold.

09:27.750 --> 09:30.292
Anything that was quarter-inch
or bigger than that

09:30.375 --> 09:32.042
got shot right out of the back.

09:32.167 --> 09:34.292
So, your big, chunky nuggets
got thrown right out the back.

09:34.417 --> 09:36.875
So, they lost
a lot of good gold.

09:37.000 --> 09:38.792
I think there's a lot
of good stuff back there.

09:38.875 --> 09:40.875
So, what's your--
what's your plan?

09:41.042 --> 09:42.667
Obviously, you want to recover
some of this gold

09:42.792 --> 09:44.000
that's overlooked.

09:44.125 --> 09:45.750
Are you interested in us
kinda helping out

09:45.875 --> 09:47.917
a little bit on this?
'Cause this sounds really cool.

09:48.042 --> 09:51.667
We-- we need some expertise,
some advice.

09:51.792 --> 09:54.958
We know you guys have been doing
digging for a long time,

09:55.042 --> 09:57.667
and you know, whatever you guys
can do to help us out,

09:57.750 --> 09:59.750
man, I tell you,
it would be a blessing.

09:59.875 --> 10:01.333
We-we really could
use your help.

10:01.417 --> 10:03.750
I'm intrigued enough
to suggest this.

10:03.875 --> 10:05.333
Matty, you'd be--
you're up for it, right?

10:05.458 --> 10:06.542
-Oh, of course.
-He's good with a shovel.

10:06.708 --> 10:08.625
-Yeah.
-But then, isn't there

10:08.708 --> 10:10.333
another component to this
when you search

10:10.417 --> 10:12.625
those old tailings piles,

10:12.750 --> 10:14.083
there's stuff that might
be left there.

10:14.208 --> 10:16.083
-That's right.
-We know it's there for a fact.

10:16.208 --> 10:18.625
-They need a metal detector.
-Definitely.

10:18.708 --> 10:21.625
Why don't we send Matty
and a metal-detecting expert

10:21.708 --> 10:23.333
along with him?

10:23.500 --> 10:25.417
He can do the first sort of
interaction with you guys,

10:25.542 --> 10:27.000
and then we can go from there.

10:27.125 --> 10:29.000
I mean, it sounds like
a real interesting thing.

10:29.167 --> 10:30.625
MATTY: I do know
the metal detectorist,

10:30.708 --> 10:32.875
and she's good.

10:33.000 --> 10:36.333
She knows her coins,
she knows her precious metals.

10:36.417 --> 10:38.417
Why don't we put her
on your team?

10:38.542 --> 10:39.792
-Okay.
-MARTY: If she's willing,
of course.

10:39.917 --> 10:41.458
I think she's more than willing,
yeah.

10:41.542 --> 10:43.458
All right, let's just
get after it, then.

10:43.542 --> 10:45.333
-What do you say?
-I'm ready, guys.

10:45.500 --> 10:47.750
I-I can't wait to see you guys.

10:47.875 --> 10:50.000
You'll have a Yankee
down in the South.

10:50.125 --> 10:52.542
-I'd love to look for
some gold with you.
-We will, come on!

10:52.708 --> 10:54.042
(laughter)

10:54.208 --> 10:56.000
All right, go dig up
a dredge, Matty.

10:57.375 --> 10:58.875
RICK:
Go dig up some gold.

11:05.000 --> 11:08.125
Well, we made it, Nikoline,
we're here.

11:08.250 --> 11:11.542
I know.
It's so beautiful down here.

11:11.708 --> 11:12.833
Two New Englanders
in the South.

11:12.958 --> 11:15.708
-Let's go.
-(chuckles) All right.

11:15.833 --> 11:18.167
NARRATOR: In Nash County,
North Carolina,

11:18.292 --> 11:21.042
Matty Blake
and metal detection expert

11:21.208 --> 11:23.833
Nikoline Bohr are heading
to the property

11:23.917 --> 11:25.833
of father and son
treasure hunters

11:26.000 --> 11:29.042
Tim and Ross Fisher
to help them search for gold

11:29.167 --> 11:33.250
believed to be contained on
a 19th-century mining dredge.

11:33.375 --> 11:36.958
Out of your list of ethics,
like, what's your golden rule?

11:37.042 --> 11:40.125
If you had to pick one, like,
when you're treasure hunting,

11:40.208 --> 11:41.792
-what's the number-one
golden rule, do you think?
-Uh...

11:41.875 --> 11:43.583
I think the most important,

11:43.708 --> 11:45.167
and probably
the least talked about

11:45.292 --> 11:48.375
is respecting the history
that you're hunting for.

11:48.500 --> 11:51.667
Yes. Your love of history

11:51.833 --> 11:54.167
-is really palpable.
-Mm-hmm.

11:54.250 --> 11:56.875
And I know that Rick and Marty
really appreciate that.

11:57.000 --> 11:58.667
-Yes.
-How are you feeling

11:58.792 --> 12:00.375
about finding gold
in the next couple days?

12:00.500 --> 12:02.333
Excited, thrilled.

12:03.708 --> 12:05.208
NARRATOR:
Originally from Denmark,

12:05.333 --> 12:08.125
Nikoline Bohr has spent
the last seven years

12:08.208 --> 12:11.125
living on Nantucket Island
in Massachusetts.

12:11.208 --> 12:13.708
While searching
colonial-era sites

12:13.833 --> 12:15.833
along the Eastern Seaboard,

12:15.958 --> 12:19.125
she has made numerous historic
and valuable discoveries.

12:19.208 --> 12:21.667
NIKOLINE: Most people think
of a treasure hunter

12:21.792 --> 12:25.250
as someone who is going
out there to get rich

12:25.375 --> 12:26.917
as fast as they can.

12:27.042 --> 12:29.292
For me, treasure hunting
is a little bit different.

12:29.375 --> 12:32.625
For me, treasure is anything
that begins

12:32.750 --> 12:35.667
or continues to tell the story

12:35.750 --> 12:37.750
of the land that it's on--

12:37.875 --> 12:41.125
that can further
